						<tr>
							<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Well, my first impression - I'm really disappointed in this change.
<br />

<br />
Although the previous skills were way out of whack (as in there were some choices which were clearly better than others) I thought the concept was great.  It allowed each player to be somewhat distinctive.  If all the choices were equally good, it would allow 4^5 (over 1000) possible combinations of chosen class skills, and let each player be a bit distinctive.
<br />

<br />
The distinctiveness allowed some dedicated players who have less free time to play to have some skills of their own to contribute, that a more hardcore player of the same class in a group might not.  I'm not trying to be a doomsayer ("eq2 is dead for the casual gamer") or something that drastic, nor am I suggesting that the game should not reward those who play it a lot, but it is against what I thought was one of eq2's strongpoints, that more casual playstyles could still feel comfortable.
<br />

<br />
Given equal skill, two people could have different impact on different situations in the game, which was kinda fun.  Now it's just a free skill raise to master level.
<br />

<br />

<br />
On a tangent - I didn't realize, though I expected, that the level cap was being raised to 60.  I really think they should find alternate means to advance characters that have hit 50.  Feels like eq1 again, where a year from now new players will feel overwhelmed with the task of leveling.  I'd rather see something like aa's, or 'rolling' introduced (Rolling was what we called in the old MUD days on certain MUD's when you'd hit 50, 100, whatever level, you'd get to start again at 1, but with better stats or abilities, etc).
<br />

<br />
I hope eq2 continues to be fun for the more casual gamer, as it was billed when introduced.
<br />

<br />
Dretch, 43rd season dirge Lucan D</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
						</tr>
					</table></td>
				</tr>
