						<tr>
							<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Hi Claire,
<br />

<br />
I'm not really sure on some of the things as far as what you meant about balance and how to acheive it, but do you really think raising the level cap another 10 is going to keep someone like yourself, who's pretty much seen all there is to see and done everything there is to do with the current game, happy for that long?  As you said, you've been killing the same stuff for a while now.  I mean that as an honest question (realize it comes out sounding snippy).  I don't think SOE has the staff or the resources, big as they are, to keep on expanding the game at such a rate as to keep the most frequent players satisfied.  At the same time, when they do try to, as I mentioned before, newer players in another two years will be left in the dust.
<br />

<br />
I do not suggest that the game not reward those who play often (and I said that in my post), but there is a point at which the game should be capped.
<br />

<br />
I would rather see them expand the level 50 content before upping the level limit.
<br />

<br />
Or introduce more dynamic or non-level dependant content - IE wars between cities with fluxuating ownership, or LDoN style zones with point-buyable gear, or ownership of homes, guildhouses, stores, etc outside the current apartments, zones with random maps, more in-game gm events, limited arena-style pvp and/or pvp servers, multi-classing systems, more ongoing storylines, more long ring events/quests.
<br />

<br />
I could literally write two more paragraphs of ideas there for added content which maintains existing level limits.  I know my ideas aren't total trash - I think there's at least one there that any given player would like to see.
<br />

<br />
If ones goal ultimately is to own the best stuff and be the highest level, then a certain percentage (possibly high, or simply more vocal due to their dedication) of players is always going to be bored, except for a little lag time after the new expansion comes out and their equally well leveled and equipped guild wipes it out.  This time will be even shorter than eq1 due to the groupX4 limit on zones, since the logistics in getting together 24 players are a lot less than 120 like some zerg style eq1 zones.
<br />

<br />
Upping level limits or equipment stats in games eventually isn't much more than scaling up existing content.  Just take a look at Deer in eq2.  They're in half or more of the outdoor zones, and take up about every level range possible, but ultimately it's just a different name, higher stats, and drop a more expensive antler.
<br />

<br />
The solution is more dynamic and horizontal content to see, and a greater variety of things to choose to do each day.  Vertical advancement doesn't give you more to do each day, just more to do for a while.
<br />

<br />
Oh - as a by the way - I've been playing from the beginning and have a lot more free time on my hands during the slow season at work, so I'll be 50 before long, and consider myself to be speaking as a more dedicated, and certainly not too casual player.  With a fairly high level guild, I've seen alot of end game content and don't look forward to hitting 60 just to see the same stuff with a new suit on.
<br />

<br />
Whew, I really rambled there.  Can you tell I'm having a long dull day at work?  Grats to anyone who made it all the way thru my post!
<br />

<br />
Dretch, 43rd stanza dirge, Lucan D</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
						</tr>
					</table></td>
				</tr>
